{"id":"2005.02932","submitter":"Francesca Fedele","authors":"Francesca Fedele","title":"Properties of triangulated and quotient categories arising from\n  $n$-Calabi-Yau triples","comments":"17 pages. Final accepted version to appear in the Pacific Journal of\n  Mathematics","journal-ref":"Pacific J. Math. 310 (2021) 1-21","doi":"10.2140/pjm.2021.310.1","report-no":null,"categories":"math.RT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The original definition of cluster algebras by Fomin and Zelevinsky has been\ncategorified and generalised in several ways over the course of the past 20\nyears, giving rise to cluster theory. This study lead to Iyama and Yang's\ngeneralised cluster categories $\\mathcal{T}/\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$ coming from\n$n$-Calabi-Yau triples $(\\mathcal{T}, \\mathcal{T}^{fd}, \\mathcal{M})$. In this\npaper, we use some classic tools of homological algebra to give a deeper\nunderstanding of such categories $\\mathcal{T}/\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$.\n  Let $k$ be a field, $n\\geq 3$ an integer and $\\mathcal{T}$ a $k$-linear\ntriangulated category with a triangulated subcategory $\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$ and a\nsubcategory $\\mathcal{M}=\\text{add}(M)$ such that $(\\mathcal{T},\n\\mathcal{T}^{fd}, \\mathcal{M})$ is an $n$-Calabi-Yau triple. In this paper, we\nprove some properties of the triangulated categories $\\mathcal{T}$ and\n$\\mathcal{T}/\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$. Our first result gives a relation between the\nHom-spaces in these categories, using limits and colimits. Our second result is\na Gap Theorem in $\\mathcal{T}$, showing when the truncation triangles split.\n  Moreover, we apply our two theorems to present an alternative proof to a\nresult by Guo, originally stated in a more specific setup of dg $k$-algebras\n$A$ and subcategories of the derived category of dg $A$-modules. This proves\nthat $\\mathcal{T}/\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$ is Hom-finite and $(n-1)$-Calabi-Yau, its\nobject $M$ is $(n-1)$-cluster tilting and the endomorphism algebras of $M$ over\n$\\mathcal{T}$ and over $\\mathcal{T}/\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$ are isomorphic. Note that\nthese properties make $\\mathcal{T}/\\mathcal{T}^{fd}$ a generalisation of the\ncluster category.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 May 2020 16:10:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 14 Dec 2020 11:02:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-27"}
